6. Process n queries.

For each query, read m and l, compute a[l-1] - a[m-1], and store or print. But in C, reading m and l as integers. But the Python code reads them as input().split(), which in C would be reading two integers. So for each query:

   int m, l;

   scanf("%d %d", &m, &l);

   Then compute the result as a[l-1] - a[m-1]. But wait, in the Python code, after reading m and l as strings, they convert them to integers, then do a[int(l)-1] - a[int(m)-1]. So in C, l-1 and m-1 are the indices. So:

   result = a[l-1] - a[m-1];

   Then, collect these results and print them after all queries are processed, or print them immediately.

In the Python code, the results are collected in an array and printed at the end. But for efficiency in C, perhaps it's better to print each result immediately. So, for each query:

   printf("%d\n", a[l-1] - a[m-1]); But we need to make sure that the indices l-1 and m-1 are within the bounds of the array a. For example, if the string is empty, but the code probably handles that. So assuming that the input is correct. Putting it all together. But there are some edge cases to consider. For example, if the string is length 0 (but the problem probably says the input is non-empty). Or queries where m or l are out of bounds. But the Python code assumes the input is correct. So the C code would look something like this:

#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

int main() {
    char soz[100001];
    scanf("%100000s", soz);
    int len = strlen(soz);
    int *a = calloc(len + 1, sizeof(int)); // initializes to 0
    for (int i = 1; i < len; i++) {
        a[i] = a[i-1];
        if (soz[i-1] == soz[i]) {
            a[i]++;
        }
    }
    int n;
    scanf("%d", &n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int m, l;
        scanf("%d %d", &m, &l);
        printf("%d\n", a[l-1] - a[m-1]);
    }
    free(a);
    return 0;
} Wait, but in the Python code, after the loop, the array a is [0, ...] up to a[len(soz)], which in C would be a[len]. But in the loop, i runs up to len-1. For example, len is the length of the string. So for a string of length 3, the loop runs i=1 and 2. So a[1] and a[2] are filled.
